@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installation"

There are two ways to install this script:
1.Copy 'TimeSaver.rexx' to your favourite ARexx-directory and run it with
  'rx TimeSaver.rexx' as often or as little as you like.
2.Copy 'TimeSaver.rexx' and 'TimeSaver.rexx.info' into the WBStartup-drawer.
  It will then be executed on every startup.

When you run this script from Workbench or without parameters, it will
require the ReqTools and RexxReqTools-libraries in your 'LIBS:'-directory
(on it's first run only). If you don't already have them installed, you can
get them (for example) from Aminet.
--
ReqTools.library is
© Nico François & Magnus Holmgren (freely distributable)
RexxReqTools.library is
© Rafael D'Halleweyn (Freeware)
--
The script also uses the 'Date' and 'SetClock' commands supplied with every
Amiga and located in the 'C:' directory.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage"

Via CLI:
'rx TimeSaver.rexx DailyOffset/N NoDS/S'
-DailyOffset is the number of seconds your clock runs too slow/fast PER DAY
 (enter any number here, e.g. -1.5 if your clock runs 1.5 seconds too fast
 or 4.65 if your clock runs approximately 4.65 seconds too slow).
 Please Notice:
 This is not the value the clock will be offset on every invoke, but the value
 the clock IS/WOULD BE offset every 24 Hours!
-NoDS is a simple switch to deactivate the correction daylight saving times
 If not deactivated, TimeSaver.rexx will automatically re-set your clock on
 the last sundays in march and october (or on it's first run after these
 days).

Via Workbench:
On it's first run the script will (silently) assume an accurate system time
and ask you for the amount of seconds your clock goes too slow/fast per
day. Just enter any floating-point number here, postive numbers mean clock
goes too slow, negative numbers vice versa.
The required data is then written to the file 'S:TimeSaver.prefs'. On
every next run it checks this data and compares with your new time. If
needed, the script will adjust your clock and save the time.

--
Notice:
If you upgraded from version 1.0, you'll probably have to decrease your daily
offset, because of a miscalculation in the first release.
--

If you later realize that you had a wrong offset, simply delete
'S:TimeSaver.prefs' and re-run the program or edit the first number of the
second line in the prefs-file to your new settings:

For example: -Let's assume your TimeSaver.prefs-file looks like this:
              01733193
              2 0.0001421
              88 298
             -The first line contains the date/time of the last adjustment.
              (please don't edit this one)
             -The first number in the second line is the clock-offset
              (in this example the clock runs 2 seconds too slow)
              To change it, replace the 2 and insert any floating point value.
             -The second number is used internally for accuracy purposes.
              (please don't change this number)
             -The last line contains the data for the daylight saving times.
              (don't edit these)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "History"

v1.0 (17-Jan-98): initial Aminet-Release

v1.1 (17-Mar-98): second Aminet-Release

-Several Bugfixes:
 -Calculation errors, which resulted in false handling after year-changes
  and day-changes (so there were DAILY miscalculations >:-((((
 -If clock was offset for more than 1 minute, program would return error.
-Now resets the clock automatically for daylight saving times
 (can optionally be switched off)
-New command line parameters: offset (in seconds) and deactivate the
 auto-switching of daylight saving times
-Prefsfile is now written to S: instead of ENV: and ENVARC:

v1.1a/b (29-Mar-98): third Aminet-Release
-Minor Bugfix:
 -Aarggh...again got mixed up in these dailight saving times...I'm sorry :-(((

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Bugs"

Bugs/ToDo:

This program still cannot change days. So if it is run around midnight and
the clock needs to be reset to another day, it will simply exit and ask to
be run again.

@ENDNODE

